## White Wine Quality by Kristin Lynch

The data set analyzed was about the quality of white Portugese wines in 2009. There are multiple variables to test how they impact the quality rating of the wine.
Data was from this source:
P. Cortez, A. Cerdeira, F. Almeida, T. Matos and J. Reis. Modeling wine preferences by data mining from physicochemical properties. In Decision Support Systems, Elsevier, 47(4):547-553. ISSN: 0167-9236.

The fixed acidity of the wine has most values between the six to seven range. We can use log to look at this in a different way since it has a long tail.

By looking at this in log, we can see a more normal distribution.

High levels of volatile acidity can lead to an unpleasant taste according to the explanation on the data set.Im wondering if those wines that are rated over .6 would have lower ratings than the rest of the wines because most wines fell under that value and that is well over the third quartile.

Small quantities of citric acid can improve the taste of wine. I wonder if this will show in the analysis, and at what point will it stop increasing the quality?

The residual sugar was one of the most interesting variables to me because of the outliers. While sweet it normally a desired trait in some foods, in wine, it is normally in the range of 1 to 45 grams according to the information on the data set. I wonder if this has an impact on quality, since many people prefer dry wine so its more about preference and subjective.

Because of the long tail, I used the log 10 to transform this data. It shows a bimodal range of sugar, with a drop around 3. Its possible this is due to trying to classify wines as dry or sweet and three would be hard to classify. We will need to look at this closer to see its correlation to quality.

Chlorides are the salt in wine. While this has a very long tail and could be looked at in log, for this one I limited the range to .10. The third quartile starts at .05, the mean is .04 and median is .043. This variable may impact the quality, but it would only be for a very small amount.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
## 0.00900 0.03600 0.04300 0.04577 0.05000 0.34600

Free sulfur dioxide prevents microbial growth according to the information about the data set. If this does impact quality, it would not be intentional like some of the other variables such as sweetness.

Free sulfur dioxide was on the the variables that I was most curious about. The outliers are so much futher out of range than the other variables. I would like to see this on a box plot later, and would like to investigate if these were in error. This is added for purpose, not to improve the taste, but I wonder what the extreme values do to quality.

According to the data set, only amounts over 50mg are detectable. I created a new variable for a data frame that only includes the detectable sulfur amounts to use on quality at a later point. I added log to this chart of the values over 50mg to include the long tail.

The density of the wine is in the same range of water according to the text report. Water can change density at different temperatures according to google, but it is still in this range. I dont see this variable as interesting as the others as I dont think I have ever noticed a difference in my drinking water.

This graph has a normal distribution. All wines in this study are acidic. They fall between the range of vinegar and tomato juice in similar examples.

Sulphates are not added to improve quality, but instead are another variable that is added for purpose. I am curious about sulphates because it is one of the components of wine that is frequently mentioned. I wonder if it has an impact?

Alcohol is one of the variables I am most curious about. There are some varieties of wine that have more alcohol, like a port which is also very sweet. While this study is on white wines, I wonder if we will see the sugar content have a postive correlation with alcohol to balance out the taste. I also wonder how this impacts the quality rating. The median wine is 10.4, and the average is 10.51, so the measurements of center are very close.

The wine quality is evenly distributed. No wines were ranked really poor (below 3), and none were ranked really excellent (perfect 10). Most were ranked slightly above what would be an average rating of 5. The actual average was 5.78, with a median of 6. I imagine that it would be hard to be profitable with a very poor wine, so Im surprised this isnt skewed even more to the right.

Most of the variables do not show a strong correlation with quality, which is not that surprising. I originally thought that it would be a combination of variables. If one variable had such a strong correlation on quality, we probably would not see as much of a range, as it would most likely be more of a standard amount added (unless cost was a major factor). I was suprised that alcohol had the strongest correlation to quality on its own. Another surprise, is the correlation with density. I assumed this would be close to 0 but its actually stronger than more after alcohol.Ill explore that in another graph.

I had wanted to see the correlation between alcohol and sugar. I had assumed that as the alcohol content went up, more sugar would be added to help balance the strong taste. There is actually a negative correlation instead. After seeing this graph, it makes more sense that the sugar is left behind by the fermentation process, not added for taste.

I was surprised to see the negative correlation between alcohol and sugar content. The higher the alcohol, generally the lower the sugar. Its possible that is because people that typically dont enjoy wine would want something lighter and sweeter, like a wine cooler, in addition to the ferementation process itself.This does not show causation between the variables, only that a negative relationship exists.

Ive added a variable to categorize the wine into buckets based on quality. This is based on my own ideas and not listed in the explanation of the data set . The data set lists 1 as very poor, and 10 as very excellent, but there are no values at either of those numbers so those were not included.

Poor is listed as anything with a rating of less than 4 in this new dataframe. In this data set, that would only include a rating of 3. Normal is 4 and 5. Good is 6 and 7. Anything 8 and over is excellent (The range of this data set is 3 to 9.)

This is interesting, because excellent quality wines clearly have a higher average and range of alcohol percentage by volume than the other categories. Good has the largest range of values, but is still more alcohol on average than normal and poor wines. In the normal category, wines have a lower alcohol content on average than the good, but there is a string of outliers that have a very high content. Finally, Poor does have more alcohol on average than normal.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

This box plot shows the quality of wine and percentage of Alcohol by Volume. The median increases across normal, good and excellent wines. Poor wines have more alcohol by mean and median than normal wines. The average also increases at normal and up. The normal quality group has the most outliers. This information could be used to create another model excluding poor quality to predict quality by alcohol content.

Plot Two

Description Two

This graph shows the relationship between sugar and alcohol and how they were rated by category. Breaking the wines into groups by rating, helps to show that as the alcohol increases, the sugar tends to decrease and the rating tends to increase. While this seems to happen in most categories, the poor category doesnt react to these variables like the other categories.

Plot Three

Description Three

This graph shows the relationship between alcohol, sugar and density. These were the strongest of the correlations that I found between variables. As the density and sugar increase, the alcohol decreases.

Reflection

In this analysis, the strongest relationships I found were from sugar, alcohol and density. I expected sugar and alcohol to have a correlation with quality, but I was surprised it wasnt stronger. It was unexpected that density would be related. There were some variables like total sulfuric dioxide that should not have impacted the taste of the wine but did show changes related to quality in the detectable range.
I think this data range should either contain wines of the same price range, or it should include the price. While amounts of variables were measured, quality of the grapes or ingredients were not. I would suspect an $800 bottle of wine would rate much higher than a $10 bottle with similar sugar, alcohol and density amounts but it is not possible to tell with this analysis. This data set could be used create an algorithm for people to answer a few questions on preferences and then create a suggestion list. It could be used by a grocery store to feature certain wines that would rate higher with more consumers.
